\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 integral is zero, and hence, changing variables to 
\begin_inset Formula $u=r/R$
\end_inset

, we have: 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\int_{0}^{1}J_{m}(x_{m,n}u)\cdot J_{m}(x_{m,n'}u)\,u\,du=0
\]

\end_inset

 for different zeros 
\begin_inset Formula $n\neq n'$
\end_inset

.
 (This is a well-known identity that is used in Fourier-Bessel series expansions.
