\begin_layout Subsection*
Problem 3: Evanescent modes in waveguides (5+10+10 points)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In class, we looked at 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}$
\end_inset

-polarized solutions in a 2d metallic waveguide, formed by an 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=\mu=1$
\end_inset

 region between two PEC walls at 
\begin_inset Formula $x=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x=L$
\end_inset

, and found that (in the absence of sources) it satisfied the eigen-equation
 
\begin_inset Formula $-\nabla^{2}H_{z}=\omega^{2}H_{z}$
\end_inset

 (for 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon_{0}=\mu_{0}=1$
\end_inset

 units) with ``Neumann'' boundary conditions 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}'(0)=H_{z}'(L)=0$
\end_inset

.
 Exploiting translational symmetry in 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

, we looked for solutions 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{z}(x,y)=u_{k}(x)e^{iky}$
\end_inset

 with a given propagation constant (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

wavevector
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) 
\begin_inset Formula $k\in\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

, and found 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
